arch, including talent testing, pilot testing, series maintenance, brand studies, and new show “ideation,” providing examples from a range of programming including news, sitcoms, reality shows, and dramas. He looks at brand studies for networks such as E!, and examines how the brands of individuals such as showrunner Ryan Murphy can be tested. Both an analytical and practical work, the book includes sample questionnaires and paths for study moderators and research analysts to follow. Drawn from over fifteen years of experience in research departments at various media companies, Creating the Viewer looks toward the future of media viewership, discussing how the concept of the viewer has changed in the age of streaming, how services such as Netflix view market research, and how viewers themselves can shift the industry through their media choices, behaviors, and activities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aTelevision broadcastingxMarketing. 0aTelevision production companiesxMarketing. 0aTelevision programsxMarketingxCase studies. 0aTelevision programsxMarketing. 0aTelevision viewersxResearchxMethodology. 0aTelevision viewersxResearch. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh  amedia industries, media research methods, primary research, television history, digital media viewership, audience studies, political economy, branding, ideation, television pilot testing, advertising effectiveness, ethnography, news media, TV showrunners, media structure and organization, media mindfulness, Media Studies, High Concept, Screening American Independent Film, 3 Women.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311079783140uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/31651140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477329078423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/